The supply of "sanctions" to Russia has fallen 100 times.
In the Government of the Russian Federation, it was estimated that the supply of agricultural products and food to Russia from countries under the Russian food embargo had decreased more than 100 times since 2013.
According to a report to the President of the Russian Federation, Vladimir Putin, in the first half of 2019, 31,000 tons of products were imported from the sanctions countries, compared with 3 million 442.2 tons in the same period in 2013, and Interfax.
However, the value of imported products fell to $226.5 million from $4 billion to $975.5 million, respectively.
This is the supply of goods that were not subject to the embargo.
As indicated in the report, the drop-out of prohibited products was offset by increased imports from CIS countries, Africa, South-East Asia, Serbia.
We recall that, at the end of August, the Government extended the rules for the destruction of agricultural products, raw materials and food, which are prohibited from entering Russia under counter-sanctions, until 31 December 2020.
The document on the official legal information portal indicated that the rules had been extended for a further year, from 31 December 2019 to 31 December 2020.
The destruction order was originally applied to products from the United States, the EU, Australia, Norway and Canada.
Subsequently, since 13 August 2015, Albania, Montenegro, Iceland, Liechtenstein and Ukraine joined the list.
A decree signed by Putin on the destruction of the "sanctions" that are being smuggled into the country (food-embargo products that Moscow introduced in response to the West's anti-Russian sanctions) entered into force in 2015.
In turn, the Government has allowed the destruction of "sanctions" food by any legal means.
As the sanctions of the West continue, the Russian Federation has also extended its response.
The measure does not apply to products that citizens import for personal use.
The ban does not apply to the import of goods for personal consumption up to 5 kg.
However, the head of the Council of the President of the Russian Federation for the Development of Civil Society and Human Rights, Mikhail Fedotov, had previously called "just immoral" the destruction of food, which he said had a negative impact on the education of people.
Moreover, the initiative to ban the destruction of food suitable for consumption was launched in early June by Rosuzuznadzor.
The Human Rights Council of the President of the Russian Federation then made a similar recommendation to the Government.
And the Vice-Prime Minister of the Russian Federation, Alexei Gordeev, said that it was not right to destroy food, and we need to think about how to use it for a purpose by assessing quality.
The head of the firm was found guilty of tax evasion
By order of the Lenin District Court of the city of Cheboksar, the Director of the Ministry of Land and Law, Vyacheslav Morozov, was found guilty of the offences provided for in article 199, paragraph 2 (b), of the Criminal Code (evasion of the payment of taxes by an organization by the inclusion in the tax declaration of a particularly large amount) and article 327, paragraph 2, of the Criminal Code (forgery of an official document granting rights and releasing it for use in order to conceal and facilitate the commission of another offence).
This is reported by the press service of the UCR's Office of the Dutchman.
From January 2008 to December 2009, Vyacheslav Morozov included information on outstanding transactions in the LEA tax records.
According to the fictitious documents, the company incurred additional costs and, therefore, the value-added taxes and the profits of the organization were reduced.
Vyacheslav Morozov was sentenced to 3.5 years & apos; imprisonment on probation.
