In Chile, a 1 billion euros telescope has been built.
This is reported by TASS with reference to the press service of the European Southern Observatory (ECO).
According to ESO, the construction of the E-ELT building dome (European Extremely Large Telescope - "European Superlarge Telescope") has been officially started this week, while the most expensive and ambitious ground-based astronomical project is being implemented.
Its total value is estimated by ESO to exceed a billion euros.
Most of this money will be spent on the construction of equipment and the building of the observatory.
The most expensive and complex component of the telescope is its record large mirror, with a diameter of about 39 metres.
It will be collected from 798 six-angle segments with a size of 1.4 metres.
It is a huge mirror, as well as two supporting reflecting surfaces of 4.2 and 3.75 metres diameter, that will help E-ELT to obtain the first detailed photographs of planets outside the solar system, stars in other galaxies, and to search for the Earth's doppelgangers.
In addition, scientists will try to use this observatory to observe the areas of Sgr A *, a supermassive black hole in the centre of the Milky Way.
Although the construction of the dome has just begun, the mirrors, scientific tools and other components of the observatory have been developed by scientists, engineers and other professionals for three years, since the first E-ELT construction plans were announced.
The contract for the production of the main mirror, with a total value of about 400 million euros, was awarded by the German firm SCHOTT and the French company Safran Reosc.
